\begin{IDEA}
**Title: Quantifying Asymmetric Transmission of Monetary Shocks on Housing Market Equilibrium**

This research employs a structural Vector Autoregression (VAR) framework to isolate the lead-lag transmission mechanisms between 30-year fixed mortgage rates, private housing starts, and the Case-Shiller National Home Price Index from 1987 to 2024. By utilizing Impulse Response Functions (IRFs), the study quantifies the time-varying elasticity of new supply (`HOUST`) and price valuation (`CSUSHPINSA`) in response to exogenous shocks in `MORTGAGE30US`. The model specifically tests for asymmetric responses, evaluating whether the market exhibits higher sensitivity to rate hikes compared to rate cuts during expansionary versus contractionary economic cycles. This approach addresses the underdetermined nature of the system by focusing on the magnitude and duration of adjustment paths rather than spectral periodicities. The resulting coefficients provide a robust empirical measure of the lag between financing cost volatility and sector-wide price discovery, effectively isolating the dynamic feedback between borrowing costs and supply-side activity.
\end{IDEA}


